    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-21T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-21T22:00:00-05:00" n="516"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">831.24/53a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-21T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 21, 1941—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>136. The Department on July 18 handed to the Venezuelan Chargé d’Affaires<note
                        n="8" xml:id="d516fn8">Arturo Lares.</note> a draft of basic agreement for
                    the lend-lease program of transferring military matériel to Venezuela. The
                    principal financial provisions are as follows: Venezuela is to receive a total
                    of $20,000,000 of war and navy matériel of which it is expected $5,000,000 of
                    army matériel and $1,000,000 of navy matériel will be transferred during the
                    fiscal year ending June 30, 1942. This delivery date is subject to change if
                    broad defense considerations so require.</p>
                <pb facs="0618" n="610" xml:id="pg_610"/>
                <p>With respect to repayment Venezuela is expected to pay $1,500,000 in each fiscal
                    year until 1947, making a total of $9,000,000 to be repaid prior to June 30,
                    1947. In consideration of the broad objectives of the program and of certain
                    very general economic concepts, the entire obligation of Venezuela to the United
                    States would be considered discharged by such payments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
